description: Ultimately from Latin retrōcēdere, from retrō- (“back, backward”) + cēdere (“to go, go back, give, return, &c.”). Equivalent to retro- +‎ cede.

verbs.description: retrocede (third-person singular simple present retrocedes, present participle retroceding, simple past and past participle retroceded)

examples: to retrocede a territory to a former proprietor
Hospitals retrenched in the '30s while the general practitioners retroceded into a bygone era.
